47 to 1648","1581":"1581","1648":"1648","1669":"1669","Foyers, Inverness-shire, Scotland":"Foyers, Inverness-shire, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"–from about 1647 to 1648":"–from about 1647 to 1648","–1648":"–1648","–Male":"Deceased","1601–Female":"1601–Deceased","1623–1669":"1623–1669","–Female":"Deceased","–1632":"–1632","1581–Female":"1581–Deceased","1623":"1623","1601":"1601","1632":"1632","about 1620":"about 1620","about 1632":"about 1632","from about 1647 to 1648":"from about 1647 to 1648","1581":"1581","1648":"1648","1669":"1669","Foyers, Inverness-shire, Scotland":"Foyers, Inverness-shire, Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Fraser","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: apparently a nickname from Anglo-Norman French <i>fraser(e)</i>, <i>fresere</i> ‘strawberry plant’. <i>Fresel</i> and <i>Frisel</i>, from Anglo-Norman French <i>fresel</i> ‘strawberry’, are early variants of the Fraser surname, the modern Gaelicized form of which is <b>Friseal</b>. See   Frizzell  . The crest on the Scottish family's coat of arms takes the form of a strawberry plant, but its antiquity is unknown. Claims of a habitational derivation, in particular from a place called la Frézelière in Anjou (France), are attractive but they lack verifiable evidence.","Americanized form of one or more similar (like-sounding) Jewish surnames.","History: There are two clans Fraser in Scotland, with common ancestry going back to Simon Fraser of Keith in East Lothian, who lived in the 12th century. One of these clans has its seat at Philorth Castle (subsequently re-named Cairnbulg) on the northeast coast of Scotland. Sir Alexander Fraser, 8th laird of Philorth (<i>c.</i> 1536–1623) converted the fishing village of Faithlie into the burgh of Fraserburgh in the 1590s. The other clan is Fraser of Lovat, associated mainly with the city of Inverness are. They are descended from Simon Fraser, a younger son, who lived in the early 14th century. In Gaelic, the head of Clan Fraser of Lovat is known as <i>Mac Shimi</i> ‘son of Simon’."],"variants":[{"name":"Frayser","meanings":["Probably an altered form of   Fraser  ."]},{"name":"Frasier","meanings":["Scottish and northern Irish: variant of   Fraser  ."]},{"name":"Frasure","meanings":["Altered form of Scottish   Fraser  ."]},{"name":"Frazer","meanings":["Variant of   Fraser  , associated chiefly with northern Ireland."]},{"name":"Fraizer","meanings":["Altered form of Scottish   Fraser  ."]},{"name":"Frashier","meanings":["Scottish and northern Irish: variant of   Fraser  ."]},{"name":"Fraiser","meanings":["Altered form of Scottish   Fraser  ."]},{"name":"Frizzell","meanings":["English and Irish: nickname from Old French <i>fresel</i>, <i>frisel</i> ‘lace, ribbon, braid, brooch, frill, ruff’, for someone with an ornate style of dress, or ‘object of little value’ (a diminutive of <i>frese</i>, of ancient Germanic origin).","Scottish: from Anglo-Norman French <i>fresel</i> ‘strawberry’, an alternative form of   Fraser  ."]},{"name":"Frazier","meanings":["English and Scottish: variant of   Fraser  .","Americanized form of French <b>Frégeau</b> (see   Fregeau  )."]},{"name":"Frasher","meanings":["Scottish and northern Irish: variant of   Fraser  .","Possibly an altered form of German <b>Fratzscher</b> (see   Frutchey  )."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"William Fraser 6th of Foyers was born as the son of Hugh-mac-William Fraser 5th of Foyers and Margaret-nic-John Mackenzie of Gairloch. He married Janet-nic-John MacPherson of Nuid about 1620, in Foyers, Inverness-shire, Scotland, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. He died from about 1647 to 1648."},"et":{"–from about 1647 to 1648":"–umbes 1647 kuni 1648","–1648":"–1648","–Male":"Surnud","1601–Female":"1601–Surnud","1623–1669":"1623–1669","–Female":"Surnud","–1632":"–1632","1581–Female":"1581–Surnud","1623":"1623","1601":"1601","1632":"1632","about 1620":"umbes 1620","about 1632":"umbes 1632","from about 1647 to 1648":"umbes 1647 kuni 1648","1581":"1581","1648":"1648","1669":"1669","Foyers, Inverness-shire, Scotland":"Foyers, Inverness-shire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"–from about 1647 to 1648":"–vuodesta noin 1647 vuoteen 1648","–1648":"–1648","–Male":"Kuollut","1601–Female":"1601–Kuollut","1623–1669":"1623–1669","–Female":"Kuollut","–1632":"–1632","1581–Female":"1581–Kuollut","1623":"1623","1601":"1601","1632":"1632","about 1620":"noin 1620","about 1632":"noin 1632","from about 1647 to 1648":"vuodesta noin 1647 vuoteen 1648","1581":"1581","1648":"1648","1669":"1669","Foyers, Inverness-shire, Scotland":"Foyers, Inverness-shire, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"–from about 1647 to 1648":"–du environ 1647 au 1648","–1648":"–1648","–Male":"Décédé","1601–Female":"1601–Décédée","1623–1669":"1623–1669","–Female":"Décédée","–1632":"–1632","1581–Female":"1581–Décédée","1623":"1623","1601":"1601","1632":"1632","about 1620":"environ 1620","about 1632":"environ 1632","from about 1647 to 1648":"du environ 1647 au 1648","1581":"1581","1648":"1648","1669":"1669","Foyers, Inverness-shire, Scotland":"Foyers, Inverness-shire, Écosse, Royaume-Uni","lifeS